      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="mountain" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Silica — Structural Mineral</strong>
        <p>Silica provides the mineral matrix for keratin cross-linking — the bonds that give nails their rigidity and resistance to breakage. Bamboo extract is the richest natural silica source. A study in Archives of Dermatological Research showed silica improved nail brittleness scores significantly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Collagen — Nail Bed Support</strong>
        <p>Collagen peptides support the nail bed — the tissue beneath the nail plate where blood vessels deliver nutrients to the nail matrix. Stronger nail bed tissue means better nutrient delivery and healthier nail growth from the source.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Iron — Oxygen Delivery</strong>
        <p>Iron-containing hemoglobin delivers oxygen to the rapidly dividing nail matrix cells. Iron deficiency (common in women) causes koilonychia (spoon-shaped nails), ridges, and brittleness. Correcting iron deficiency often resolves nail problems within 6 months.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>The FDA issued a safety communication in 2017 warning that <strong>high-dose biotin can interfere with certain laboratory tests</strong>, including thyroid panels and cardiac troponin. If you take biotin supplements (2,500mcg+), stop supplementation 72 hours before blood work and inform your healthcare provider. This does not affect biotin's safety for nail health — only its interaction with specific diagnostic tests.</p>
      <cite>FDA Safety Communication — Biotin Interference with Lab Tests</cite>
    </div>

