    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Nails</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do nail gummies actually work?</summary><p>Yes. 2,500mcg biotin increased nail thickness 25% in 6 months. Biotin reduced splitting in 63% of brittle nail patients. Silica and collagen provide additional structural support. Results require 3-6 months of consistent daily use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take to see results?</summary><p>Fingernails grow 3-4mm/month. Reduced breakage noticeable at 2-3 months. Fully renewed stronger nails at 4-6 months. Toenails take 12-18 months. Clinical studies use 6-month timeframes.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What causes brittle nails?</summary><p>Nutritional deficiencies (biotin, iron, zinc), water exposure, chemicals, gel/acrylic nails, hypothyroidism, anemia, aging, and certain medications. Address the underlying cause while supplementing for best results.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much biotin do I need for nails?</summary><p>Clinical dose: 2,500-5,000mcg daily (83-167x the 30mcg general RDA). Higher doses have not shown additional nail benefit. Water-soluble, so excess is safely excreted. Inform your doctor before blood work.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can biotin interfere with lab tests?</summary><p>Yes. High-dose biotin affects thyroid panels, troponin, and hormone tests using biotin-streptavidin immunoassays. Stop biotin 72 hours before blood work. The FDA has issued a safety communication about this.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are nail gummies the same as hair gummies?</summary><p>Largely yes. Both hair and nails are keratin-based. Biotin, silica, collagen, zinc, and vitamin C support both. Marketing focus differs. For nails specifically, prioritize biotin (2,500mcg+), silica, and iron.</p></details>

